player.seasonOutlook: The Jets finished 22nd in D/ST fantasy points last season, which was their fifth finish worse than 20th in the past six seasons. The Jets ranked near mid-pack in most categories. They ranked poorly in yards allowed (eighth-worst) and points allowed (fourth-worst) but were strong in blocks (second) and touchdowns (five). The defense includes a lot of talent, including Jamal Adams, Leonard Williams, Henry Anderson, Trumaine Johnson, Avery Williamson, C.J. Mosley and Quinnen Williams, though cornerback depth and edge rush are major concerns. This is a sleeper unit to keep in mind in deeper leagues.

Green Bay's D/ST ranked 23rd in fantasy points last season, which marked the unit's third consecutive finish outside the top 20. The Packers struggled badly in most departments, ranking 29th in interceptions (seven) and forced turnovers (15), 26th in tackles for loss (80), 15th in yardage allowed (5,670) and 11th in points allowed (400). On the plus side, the unit ranked eighth with 44 sacks, which marks the Packers' seventh top-10 finish in the category the past nine seasons. Muhammad Wilkerson and Nick Perry (both barely played last season), as well as Clay Matthews, are gone, but Adrian Amos, Preston Smith, Za'Darius Smith, Rashan Gary and Darnell Savage were key offseason additions. They join Kenny Clark, Mike Daniels, Blake Martinez and Jaire Alexander to form an intriguing sleeper D/ST.

The Seattle D/ST finished 14th in fantasy points last season, which marks its first finish worse than ninth since 2010. Seattle ranked 18th in interceptions (12), 24th in tackles for loss (82) and 25th in yards per play (5.92). The unit was 10th in forced turnovers (26) and 11th in points allowed (347), though a league-high 14 fumble recoveries will be hard to repeat. The Seahawks failed to make any impact veteran additions, despite watching Earl Thomas, Frank Clark and Justin Coleman depart. This is a defense with good coaching but very shaky personnel behind Bobby Wagner, K.J. Wright, Bradley McDougald and first-round pick L.J. Collier. Add and start the Seattle D/ST only when the unit is at home and the matchup is good. That will be the case in Week 1 against the Bengals.

Carolina operated its pass-heaviest offense during the Cam Newton era last season, which led to a third wide receiver seeing the field on 85% of its pass plays. That was third highest in the NFL. Wright quietly caught 43 passes for 447 yards last season while focusing his time on the short area (6.0 aDOT was second-lowest at the position and his 74% catch rate was sixth best). His role, as well as the presence of Christian McCaffrey, DJ Moore, Curtis Samuel and Greg Olsen, severely limits his fantasy appeal, though it's fair to say he's among the deepest of sleepers in oversized PPR leagues.

The Vikings have ranked right around league average in three-plus wide sets during each of Mike Zimmer's five seasons as the team's head coach. That includes 13th (79%) last season. Beebe, who went undrafted last year, made a brief appearance as a rookie, catching all four of his targets for 39 yards. The 25-year-old slot receiver has an opportunity to earn a significant role between Stefon Diggs and Adam Thielen, though Jordan Taylor and Laquon Treadwell are also in the mix. Minnesota's run-first offense figures to significantly cap the fantasy value of whomever looks down the gig.

The Chargers increased their usage of three-plus wide receiver sets from 71% in 2017 (Anthony Lynn's first season as head coach) to 78% last season. The change was predictable with Hunter Henry out and with Mike Williams in his second season. Of course, with Henry back and Tyrell Williams gone, it's possible the number regresses in 2019. Benjamin is a noteworthy deep sleeper, but keep in mind that the 29 year old has one Top 45 fantasy campaign to his name and that was back in 2015.

The Ravens have ranked no higher than 25th in three-plus wide receiver sets over the past five seasons. A majority of that came with Joe Flacco under center, though Baltimore ranked 26th (65%) in the category during Jackson's seven regular season starts last season. Moore very well could open the season higher on the depth chart, but third in line is a safe estimate with first-round pick Marquise Brown and slot Willie Snead in the fold. Moore, a 2016 fourth-round pick, may truly get an opportunity to break out this season, but Baltimore's run-heavy attack figures to cap the fantasy appeal of most of the team's pass catchers.

Dorsett is back with the Patriots after managing only 60 targets in 31 games since joining the team. Dorsett was a full-time player during Julian Edelman's four-game suspension last season, but was limited to a 16/165/2 line and the 45th-most fantasy points among wideouts during the span. He was a non-factor for a majority of the rest of the season and failed to finish as a Top 75 fantasy receiver for the fourth time in four NFL seasons. The 2015 first-round pick spent his early career as a downfield target, but was used more in the short area in 2018 (10.3 aDOT). He's undersized at 5-foot-10, 185 pounds and offers little near the goal line (six career touchdowns). There' sleeper appeal here only if Dorsett beats out N'Keal Harry and PUP candidate Demaryius Thomas for No. 2 duties behind Julian Edelman.

Butt is set to enter his third NFL season but has appeared in only three games thus far. Butt tore his ACL during the 2016 Orange Bowl and missed his entire rookie season after Denver selected him in the fifth round of the 2017 draft. Last season, he was targeted 12 times in three games before tearing his ACL at practice. The Michigan product is a solid pass-catcher with good hands, but he's not very fast or athletic. Butt will compete with the likes of 2019 first-round pick Noah Fant and Jeff Heuerman for starting duties, but is unlikely to see enough targets to make much noise in fantasy.

St. Brown was the third of three wide receivers selected by the Packers in the mid-to-late rounds of the 2018 draft. Though he did enough to overtake fourth-rounder J'Mon Moore on the depth chart, St. Brown was limited to 238 routes and 35 targets in 12 regular-season games. He posted a 21/328/0 receiving line and his best weekly fantasy finish was 26th. The 6-foot-5 receiver is a name to watch as he battles for No. 2/3 duties on the Packers' wide-open wide receiver depth chart, but he's barely worth considering in the late stages of your draft.

The Bears drafted Shaheen in the second round of the 2017 draft, but the massive 6-foot-6, 278-pound tight end has little fantasy appeal as the blocking complement to Trey Burton. Shaheen missed 10 games last season and handled a grand total of seven targets during the six games he was active. Shaheen could surprise with a half dozen touchdowns, but, barring a Burton injury, simply won't see enough volume to land on the fantasy radar.
